This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category as it deals with human action recognition from skeleton data. It also involves the use of Graph Convolutional Networks (GCN) which is a popular technique in the field of computer vision. 

The paper also involves Neural Architecture Search (NAS) which is a subfield of Machine Learning (cs.LG) that deals with automatically designing neural network architectures. 

The paper also involves the use of dynamic graph modules and multiple-hop modules which are techniques used in Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) for modeling complex data structures. 

The paper involves experiments on large-scale datasets which are commonly used in Multimedia (cs.MM) research. 

Finally, the paper proposes a sampling- and memory-efficient evolution strategy which is a technique used in Neural Engineering (cs.NE) for optimizing neural networks.
